@module parser
@layer 2
@lang aria
@aid_version 0.2
@purpose Recursive descent parser producing AST node pool and declaration index
@depends [lexer, diagnostic]
@workflow The parser is the second stage of the compilation pipeline. Lexer produces tokens, parser consumes them to build a flat AST node pool and a declaration index. The resolver and checker then walk the pool via DeclIndex entries.
@invariants
  - NodePool index 0 is always a sentinel EkNone node; valid node indices start at 1
  - DeclIndex index 0 is always a sentinel DkNone entry; valid decl indices start at 1
  - Child lists use indirection: EkNone nodes with c0 pointing to the actual child node
  - Parser state is threaded immutably — every mutation returns a new Parser struct
@notes
  - The AST uses a flat pool design (no recursive Expr trees) to stay within bootstrap compiler limitations (no recursive types without auto-boxing)
  - All internal parser functions use underscore prefix convention (_parse_fn, _ck, _adv, etc.)
  - The Expr struct is intentionally generic with s1/s2/b1/b2/c0/c1/c2 fields overloaded per ExprKind — see mk_* constructors for the encoding contract of each kind

---

@type ExprKind
@kind sum
@purpose Discriminator tag for AST nodes. Every syntactic construct in Aria maps to one variant. Declarations, expressions, statements, and structural nodes (params, fields, variants) all share the same Expr representation, distinguished only by this tag.
@variants
  EkIntLit — Integer literal expression
  EkFloatLit — Float literal expression
  EkStringLit — String literal expression
  EkBoolLit — Boolean literal expression
  EkIdent — Identifier reference
  EkBinary — Binary operator expression
  EkUnary — Unary operator expression
  EkCall — Function call (also used for destructure patterns in match arms)
  EkMethodCall — Method call (dot syntax)
  EkFieldAccess — Field access (dot syntax)
  EkIndex — Index expression (brackets)
  EkBlock — Block expression (braces); also used for entry blocks (s1="_entry") and test blocks (s1="_test:name")
  EkIf — If/else expression
  EkMatch — Match expression
  EkClosure — Closure expression
  EkArray — Array literal
  EkStruct — Struct literal; also used for record update (s1="_update")
  EkAssign — Assignment expression
  EkBinding — Variable binding (:= or mut)
  EkReturn — Return expression
  EkBreak — Break expression
  EkContinue — Continue expression
  EkFor — For loop
  EkWhile — While loop
  EkLoop — Infinite loop
  EkDefer — Defer expression
  EkWith — With expression (resource management)
  EkTuple — Tuple expression
  EkCatch — Catch expression (error recovery)
  EkPipeline — Pipeline expression (|>)
  EkRange — Range expression (.. or ..=)
  EkPropagate — Error propagation (?); b1=true when using transform syntax (? |e| body)
  EkAssertOk — Assert success (!)
  EkFnDecl — Function declaration
  EkTypeDecl — Type declaration (struct, sum type, newtype)
  EkEnumDecl — Enum declaration
  EkTraitDecl — Trait declaration
  EkImplDecl — Impl block declaration
  EkConstDecl — Constant declaration
  EkUseDecl — Use/import declaration
  EkParam — Function parameter
  EkField — Struct field or variant field
  EkVariant — Sum type / enum variant
  EkListComp — List comprehension [expr for x in iter where cond]
  EkYield — Yield expression
  EkSelect — Select expression (channel multiplexing)
  EkNone — Sentinel / empty; also used as indirection nodes in child lists (c0 points to actual node)
@antipatterns
  - Do not compare ExprKind values directly for dispatch; use expr_kind_name() which returns a string — this avoids bootstrap codegen issues with large sum type matching
