---

@type Expr
@kind struct
@purpose Universal AST node. All syntactic constructs use this same flat struct with fields overloaded per ExprKind. This avoids recursive types (which the bootstrap compiler cannot handle without auto-boxing) and enables a flat pool-based storage model.
@fields
  kind: ExprKind — Node type discriminator
  s1: str — Primary string payload (name, operator, literal value, binding name)
  s2: str — Secondary string payload (generic params for fn/type, trait name for impl, variant names for enum, supertrait info for trait)
  b1: bool — Primary boolean flag (is_mut for binding, has_else for if, is_sum for type, has_value for return, inclusive for range, is_tuple for variant, has_body for fn, is_self for param)
  b2: bool — Secondary boolean flag (has_ret for fn, has_generics for type)
  c0: i64 — Child node index 0 (body/condition/lhs/operand/value; type_tok_pos for param/field)
  c1: i64 — Child node index 1 (then_branch/rhs/body; ret_tok_pos for fn)
  c2: i64 — Child node index 2 (else_branch; err_tok_pos for fn)
  list_start: i64 — Start index into pool for child lists (params, fields, variants, args, stmts)
  list_count: i64 — Number of children in list (param_count, field_count, arm_count, etc.)
  span: Span — Source location
@invariants
  - c0/c1/c2 are pool indices; 0 means "no child" (index 0 is the sentinel)
  - list_start..list_start+list_count are EkNone indirection nodes whose c0 fields point to actual child nodes
  - For match arms: list uses pairs (pattern, body) so actual pool entries = list_count * 2
  - For select arms: list uses pairs (arm_info, body) so actual pool entries = list_count * 2
@source_file src/parser/ast.aria
