@fn parse
@sig (tokens: [Token]) -> PR
@purpose Top-level parse entry point. Consumes a full token stream and produces a root EkBlock node containing all top-level declarations as children. Handles mod declaration, use declarations, and iterates over all top-level forms.
@calls [new_parser, _skip_nl, _parse_top, _padd, _pidx]
@pre tokens is a complete lexer output ending with TkEof
@post PR.e is an EkBlock with list_start/list_count covering all top-level declarations
@effects Builds the full NodePool as a side effect of parsing
@workflow Called by build_decl_index to produce the full AST pool, which is then bridged to the DeclIndex for downstream stages.
@notes The root block's children are EkNone indirection nodes whose c0 fields point to the actual declaration nodes. Skips the sentinel token at index 0 if present.
[src: src/parser/parser.aria:112-167]
@source_file src/parser/parser.aria
@source_line 112

---

@fn build_decl_index
@sig (tokens: [Token]) -> ParseResult
@purpose Main entry point for the parser module. Performs two passes: (1) a fast token scan to build the DeclIndex with token ranges, then (2) a full parse via parse() to build the AST pool, and finally bridges node_idx values into the DeclIndex entries.
@calls [new_parser, parse, _bridge_ast_to_decl_index]
@pre tokens is a complete lexer output ending with TkEof
@post ParseResult.index has all top-level declarations with node_idx populated; ParseResult.pool has the complete AST
@workflow This is the function that downstream stages (resolver, checker) call. The DeclIndex allows them to look up and process individual declarations without re-parsing.
@notes
  - The two-pass approach is intentional: the token scan is fast and gives the resolver declaration boundaries early, while the full parse provides the AST nodes
  - Handles pub visibility, annotations (@attr), all declaration keywords (fn, type, struct, enum, trait, impl, const, entry, test, bench, extern, alias, before, after)
  - The _bridge_ast_to_decl_index function matches DeclIndex entries to AST nodes by name and kind, setting the node_idx field
