@fn infix_binding_power
@sig (kind: TokenKind) -> BindingPower
@purpose Returns the left and right binding powers for an infix operator token. The Pratt parser uses these to determine operator precedence and associativity. Returns no_binding_power() for non-operator tokens.
@notes Precedence levels (ascending): 10=assignment/binding, 20=pipeline, 30=null coalesce, 40=logical OR, 50=logical AND, 60=comparison, 70=range, 80=bitwise OR, 90=XOR, 100=bitwise AND, 110=shift, 120=additive, 130=multiplicative. Comparison and range are non-associative (left==right). Assignment is non-associative.
[src: src/parser/precedence.aria:24-78]
@source_file src/parser/precedence.aria
@source_line 24

---

@fn prefix_binding_power
@sig (kind: TokenKind) -> i64
@purpose Returns the binding power for a prefix unary operator (-, !, ~). Returns 0 for non-prefix tokens. Prefix operators bind at level 140, tighter than all infix operators.
@source_file src/parser/precedence.aria
@source_line 82

---

@fn postfix_binding_power
@sig (kind: TokenKind) -> i64
@purpose Returns the binding power for a postfix operator or postfix-position token. Returns 0 for non-postfix tokens. Level 150: ? (propagate), ! (assert-ok), catch. Level 160: . (field/method), ?. (optional chain), ( (call), [ (index).
@notes Postfix operators bind tighter than prefix (150/160 vs 140), ensuring correct parsing of expressions like -x.field and !result?.
@source_file src/parser/precedence.aria
